io.pivotal.rti.protocols

Class ProtocolEvent

  • java.lang.Object
    • io.pivotal.rti.protocols.ProtocolEvent

  • public class ProtocolEvent
extends java.lang.Object
    Core domain class provided through the codecs API and needed for implementing a valid ProtocolAdapter. ProtocolEvent captures domain agnostic data from a network protocol. For example, it gives an abstraction over telecommunication protocols or any other protocols from a different domain. ProtocolEvent has two layers to it. First, it has a few native fields those are common to many different kind of protocols. For example, it has a primaryId, serviceId, sourceId, temporaryId, ingestTime, other timing attributes, initial/current location id's from where the protocol occurred etc. Please see the individual methods for further explanation. Second, it has a ProtocolDetailMap that contains a key/value pair of protocol specific information. This is where the implementers of new Codecs have to put data that cannot natively be placed in a ProtocolEvent.

      • setProtocolName

        public void setProtocolName(java.lang.String protocolName)
        Name of the protocol is a unique string that is specific to this protocol. This name has to match with ProtocolAdapter.protocol() as this is used as a link between the protocol behind this event and its corresponding Codec through the adapter implementation.
        Parameters:
        protocolName - Name of the protocol

      • setKey

        public final void setKey(java.lang.String key)
        Key makes a protocol event unique from the rest. So care must be taken when generating this. Possible keys can be, but not limited to are, UUID's, randomly generated strings etc. The implementer has to make sure the uniqueness of the key.
        Parameters:
        key - unique key for this ProtocolEvent.

        public final void setServiceId(java.lang.String serviceId)

        public void setInitialLocationId(java.lang.String initialLocationId)

        public void setCurrentLocationId(java.lang.String currentLocationId)
